SIMPLE: farm
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Farm
<hw>Farm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>ferme</ets>
rent, lease, F. <ets>ferme</ets>, LL. <ets>firma</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>firmus</ets> firm, fast, <ets>firmare</ets> to make firm or fast.
See <er>Firm</er>, <pos>a. & n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The rent
of land, -- originally paid by reservation of part of its
products.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The term or tenure of a lease of land for
cultivation; a leasehold.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is great willfulness in landlords to make any longer
<qex>farms</qex> to their tenants.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The land held under lease and by payment of rent for
the purpose of cultivation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Any tract of land devoted to agricultural purposes,
under the management of a tenant or the owner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In English the ideas of a lease, a term, and a rent,
continue to be in a great degree inseparable, even from the popular
meaning of a <xex>farm</xex>, as they are entirely so from the legal
sense.</note> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A district of country leased (or farmed) out for the
collection of the revenues of government.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The province was devided into twelve <qex>farms</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld> <def>A lease of the imposts on
particular goods; <as>as, the sugar <ex>farm</ex>, the silk
<ex>farm</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whereas G. H. held the <qex>farm</qex> of sugars upon a rent of
10,000 marks per annum.</q> <rj><qau>State Trials (1196).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Farm</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Farm
<hw>Farm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Farmed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Farming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lease or let for
an equivalent, as land for a rent; to yield the use of to
proceeds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are enforced to <qex>farm</qex> our royal realm.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give up to another, as an estate, a business, the
revenue, etc., on condition of receiving in return a percentage of what
it yields; <as>as, to <ex>farm</ex> the taxes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>farm</qex> their subjects and their duties toward
these.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To take at a certain rent or rate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To devote (land) to agriculture; to cultivate, as
land; to till, as a farm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To farm let</b></col>, <col><b>To let to
farm</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to lease on rent.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Farm</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Farm
<hw>Farm</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To engage in the business of
tilling the soil; to labor as a farmer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Farmable</ent>⟦br⟧
